{{IPAchar|/wo/}} → {{IPAchar|/o/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=お|-}}.  Found in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'', completed some time after 759 CE.<ref>{{RQ:Manyoshu|14|3484}}, text [http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man14Yo.html#3484 here]</ref>

* {{sense|hemp}} {{ja-r|麻|あさ}}
* {{sense|ramie}} {{ja-r|苧|からむし}}
* {{sense|thread, in general}} {{ja-r|糸|いと}}

{{ja-noun|むし}}

# {{lb|ja|sort=むし|obsolete}} old name for ''karamushi'': the [[ramie]] plant, {{taxlink|Boehmeria nivea var. nipononivea|variety|noshow=1}}
# short for {{ja-r|帔|むしのたれぎぬ|rom=-}}, {{ja-r|枲の垂れ衣|むし の たれぎぬ}}, a kind of [[veil]] made of [[ramie]] and worn from the [[brim]] of a hat by women from the {{w|Heian period}} through the {{w|Kamakura period}}

{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|からむし}}

Appears to be a compound of {{compound|ja|sort=からむし|殻|tr1=kara|t1=husk|苧|tr2=mushi|t2=ramie fiber}}.

Some sources suggest that the ''mushi'' component derives from {{m|ja|蒸し|tr=mushi||steaming}}, from verb {{m|ja|蒸す|tr=musu||to steam something; to be steamy or muggy}}. However, ramie is not processed using steam, so these are more likely to be [[folk etymology|folk etymologies]].

{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|からんし}}

{{IPAchar|/karamuɕi/}} → {{IPAchar|/karanɕi/}}

Alteration from ''karamushi''. Rare and obsolete reading.

{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|こるむし}}

{{IPAchar|/karamuɕi/}} → {{IPAchar|/korumuɕi/}}

Alteration from ''karamushi''. Rare and obsolete reading.

